[[de:Millionenjahrhaus]]
{{translated page|de|Haus der Millionen|version=243359763|comment=Imported full de history}}

{{Infobox Hieroglyphen
|TITEL               = Million‑year house
|NAME                = <hiero>O6-X1:O1-N35:X1-C11-Z3-G17-M4-M4-M4</hiero><br/>Hut‑net‑hehu‑em‑renput<br/>''Ḥw.t‑n.t‑ḥḥw‑m‑rnp.wt''<br/>“House of Millions of Years”
}}

[[Datei:Karte grabstätten theben west.png|mini|Temple landscape on the west bank of the Nile at Thebes]]

The '''million‑year house''' (also '''house of millions of years, Millionenjahrhaus''') is a term that first appears at the end of the {{ill|Middle Kingdom of Egypt|de|Mittleres Reich (Ägypten)|ja|エジプト中王国|zh|埃及中王国}} and originally denoted a temple for the royal cult. In the {{ill|New Kingdom of Egypt|de|Neues Reich (Ägypten)|ja|エジプト新王国|zh|埃及新王国}} it came to refer above all to the royal {{ill|mortuary temple|de|Totentempel|ja|葬祭殿|zh|祭祀神殿}}, though other shrines of the king’s cult can also be called million‑year houses. Their imagery – both in cult statues and wall reliefs – presents a mystical union of the king with a major deity such as {{ill|Amun|de|Amun|ja|アメン|zh|阿蒙}}, {{ill|Osiris|de|Osiris|ja|オシリス|zh|奥西里斯}}, or {{ill|Ptah|de|Ptah|ja|プタハ|zh|プタハ}}, believed to guarantee the monarch’s eternal existence.citeturn0

Most million‑year houses once stood parallel to the {{ill|Nile|de|Nil|ja|ナイル川|zh|尼罗河}}, opposite the {{ill|Valley of the Kings|de|Tal der Könige|ja|王家の谷|zh|帝王谷}} at {{ill|Thebes, Egypt|de|Theben-West|ja|テーベ西岸|zh|底比斯西岸}}; others were erected at {{ill|Memphis, Egypt|de|Memphis (Ägypten)|ja|メンフィス|zh|孟斐斯}} ({{ill|Amenhotep III|de|Amenophis III.|ja|アメンホテプ3世|zh|阿蒙霍特普三世}}, {{ill|Ramesses II|de|Ramses II.|ja|ラムセス2世|zh|拉美西斯二世}}), {{ill|Abydos, Egypt|de|Abydos (Ägypten)|ja|アビドス|zh|阿比多斯}} ({{ill|Seti I|de|Sethos I.|ja|セティ1世|zh|塞提一世}}, Ramesses II), {{ill|Soleb|de|Soleb|ja|ソレブ|zh|索勒卜}} (Amenhotep III) and {{ill|Abu Simbel temples|de|Tempel von Abu Simbel|ja|アブ・シンベル神殿|zh|阿布辛拜勒神庙}} (Ramesses II). Already during their lifetimes the {{ill|pharaohs|de|Pharao|ja|ファラオ|zh|法老}} set up a monument where they themselves were venerated. Regular {{ill|barque|de|Barke|ja|聖舟|zh|圣船}} processions brought the cult image of the relevant god into the shrine. The name “house of millions” alludes to millions of years – i.e. for all eternity – during which the cult should endure.citeturn0

== Historical development ==
At the start of the {{ill|Fourth Dynasty of Egypt|de|4. Dynastie (Ägypten)|ja|エジプト第4王朝|zh|埃及第四王朝}} the *classical* pyramid complex took shape with four components – {{ill|valley temple|de|Taltempel|ja|谷神殿|zh|峡谷神庙}}, {{ill|Causeway (Ancient Egypt|de|Aufweg|lt=causeway|it|Rampa processionale|cs|Vzestupná cesta}}, mortuary temple, and {{ill|pyramid|de|Pyramide (Bauwerk)|ja|ピラミッド|zh|金字塔}} – first realised at the {{ill|Meidum Pyramid|de|Meidum-Pyramide|ja|メイドゥームのピラミッド|zh|梅杜姆金字塔}}. This layout remained standard into the Middle Kingdom.

For security reasons the {{ill|New Kingdom of Egypt|de|Neues Reich|ja|エジプト新王国|zh|埃及新王国}} moved royal burials to rock‑cut tombs in the Valley of the Kings and relocated the associated mortuary temples to the edge of the cultivable land. Occasionally the valley temple and causeway can still be traced (e.g. at the temple of {{ill|Hatshepsut|de|Hatschepsut|ja|ハトシェプスト|zh|哈特谢普苏特}}). The peak of {{ill|El Qurn|de|El-Qurn|ja|エル・クルン|zh|库恩山}} (“the Horn”), a natural pyramid above the valley, symbolically replaced the Old‑Kingdom pyramid. Million‑year houses of the New Kingdom are attested not only at Thebes but also at sites without royal tombs.

