[[File:Karte grabstätten theben west.png|thumb|Temple landscape on the west bank of the Nile at Thebes]]

The '''million‑year house''' (also '''house of millions of years, Millionenjahrhaus''') is a term that first appears at the end of the {{ill|Middle Kingdom of Egypt|en|Middle Kingdom of Egypt|qid=Q191324|lt=Middle Kingdom of Egypt|1=Middle Kingdom of Egypt}} and originally denoted a temple for the royal cult. In the {{ill|New Kingdom of Egypt|en|New Kingdom of Egypt|qid=Q180568|lt=New Kingdom of Egypt|1=New Kingdom of Egypt}} it came to refer above all to the royal {{ill|Mortuary temple|en|Mortuary temple|qid=Q927825|lt=mortuary temple|1=Mortuary temple}}, though other shrines of the king’s cult can also be called million‑year houses. Their imagery – both in cult statues and wall reliefs – presents a mystical union of the king with a major deity such as {{ill|Amun|en|Amun|qid=Q58373|lt=Amun|1=Amun}}, {{ill|Osiris|en|Osiris|qid=Q46491|lt=Osiris|1=Osiris}}, or {{ill|Ptah|en|Ptah|qid=Q146321|lt=Ptah|1=Ptah}}, believed to guarantee the monarch’s eternal existence.citeturn0

Most million‑year houses once stood parallel to the {{ill|Nile|en|Nile|qid=Q3392|lt=Nile|1=Nile}}, opposite the {{ill|Valley of the Kings|en|Valley of the Kings|qid=Q133423|lt=Valley of the Kings|1=Valley of the Kings}} at {{ill|Thebes, Egypt|de|Theben-West|ja|テーベ西岸|zh|底比斯西岸|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}; others were erected at {{ill|Memphis, Egypt|en|Memphis, Egypt|qid=Q5715|lt=Memphis, Egypt|1=Memphis, Egypt}} ({{ill|Amenhotep III|en|Amenhotep III|qid=Q42606|lt=Amenhotep III|1=Amenhotep III}}, {{ill|Ramesses II|en|Ramesses II|qid=Q1523|lt=Ramesses II|1=Ramesses II}}), {{ill|Abydos, Egypt|en|Abydos, Egypt|qid=Q192268|lt=Abydos, Egypt|1=Abydos, Egypt}} ({{ill|Seti I|en|Seti I|qid=Q157918|lt=Seti I|1=Seti I}}, Ramesses II), {{ill|Soleb|en|Soleb|qid=Q1457914|lt=Soleb|1=Soleb}} (Amenhotep III) and {{ill|Abu Simbel|en|Abu Simbel|qid=Q134140|lt=Abu Simbel temples|1=Abu Simbel}} (Ramesses II). Already during their lifetimes the {{ill|Pharaoh|en|Pharaoh|qid=Q37110|lt=pharaohs|1=Pharaoh}} set up a monument where they themselves were venerated. Regular {{ill|barque|de|Barke|ja|聖舟|zh|圣船|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} processions brought the cult image of the relevant god into the shrine. The name “house of millions” alludes to millions of years – i.e. for all eternity – during which the cult should endure.citeturn0

== Historical development ==
At the start of the {{ill|Fourth Dynasty of Egypt|en|Fourth Dynasty of Egypt|qid=Q211001|lt=Fourth Dynasty of Egypt|1=Fourth Dynasty of Egypt}} the *classical* pyramid complex took shape with four components – {{ill|Ancient Egyptian Valley Temple|lt=valley temple|de|Taltempel|ja|谷神殿|zh|峡谷神庙|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Causeway (Ancient Egypt|de|Aufweg|lt=causeway|it|Rampa processionale|cs|Vzestupná cesta}}, mortuary temple, and {{ill|Pyramid|en|Pyramid|qid=Q12516|lt=pyramid|1=Pyramid}} – first realised at the {{ill|Meidum Pyramid|de|Meidum-Pyramide|ja|メイドゥームのピラミッド|zh|梅杜姆金字塔|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. This layout remained standard into the Middle Kingdom.

For security reasons the {{ill|New Kingdom of Egypt|en|New Kingdom of Egypt|qid=Q180568|lt=New Kingdom of Egypt|1=New Kingdom of Egypt}} moved royal burials to rock‑cut tombs in the Valley of the Kings and relocated the associated mortuary temples to the edge of the cultivable land. Occasionally the valley temple and causeway can still be traced (e.g. at the temple of {{ill|Hatshepsut|en|Hatshepsut|qid=Q129234|lt=Hatshepsut|1=Hatshepsut}}). The peak of {{ill|El Qurn|en|El Qurn|qid=Q1323811|lt=El Qurn|1=El Qurn}} (“the Horn”), a natural pyramid above the valley, symbolically replaced the Old‑Kingdom pyramid. Million‑year houses of the New Kingdom are attested not only at Thebes but also at sites without royal tombs.

